    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1463564671" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1463564671" />
    <a title="Dolors" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18383778-dolors"><img alt="Dolors" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1612113597p2/18383778.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1463564671?book_show_action=true">Dec 08, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dolors" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dolors" href="/user/show/18383778-dolors">Dolors</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780486437002" href="/book/show/2327659.The_Song_of_the_Lark">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Lovers of art in all forms</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18383778-dolors?shelf=read-in-2015">read-in-2015</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1463564671" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4978252218632839888">Even though <i>The Song of the Lark</i> is the second installment in “The Prairie Trilogy”, I consider <i>Thea</i>, its strong minded protagonist, the culminating embodiment of the rest of Cather’s feisty heroines, the point where they end up converging to glow in full radiance.<br/><br/><a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[As much as <i>Ántonia</i> warmed my wistful heart in <i>My Ántonia</i>, her development as an independent human being was finally curtailed by the solemn aura of her femininity because it ended trapping her in the role of ultimate inc</span></span>
  <span id="freeText4978252218632839888" style="display:none">Even though <i>The Song of the Lark</i> is the second installment in “The Prairie Trilogy”, I consider <i>Thea</i>, its strong minded protagonist, the culminating embodiment of the rest of Cather’s feisty heroines, the point where they end up converging to glow in full radiance.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[As much as <i>Ántonia</i> warmed my wistful heart in <i>My Ántonia</i>, her development as an independent human being was finally curtailed by the solemn aura of her femininity because it ended trapping her in the role of ultimate incarnation as some kind of “earth mother”. <br />Contrarily, Thea renounces to her personal life and sacrifices having a family because she has a dream to pursue, which is also a heavy burden and an enormous responsibility, regardless of the consequences of taking the path that leads her to the art she believes to be locked inside herself, ebullient to flare up if the right igniter flashes the desired, needed spark.<br />In <i>O Pioneers!</i>, free-spirited <i>Alexandra</i> proves she is worth her weight in gold when it comes to stating her position as a successful entrepreneur without the shadow of a male presence to influence her decisions, but she proves to be severe and rushed to judge illicit love within the framework of social convention of a highly questionable morality.<br />In contrast, Thea doesn’t renounce to her self-respect but at the same time her open-mindedness allows her to accept, and even empathize with people of dubious propriety, for she challenges the generally accepted norm and forms an opinion based on her personal experience alone. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Some might perceive Thea’s attitude as self-centered, but it would be contrived to create a believable heroine whose main goal is to succeed in her professional career without leaving sentimental matters aside. Thea’s character embodies a woman confronted against an ascribed duty to her gender, which becomes her biggest enemy, but who, regardless of the spiteful, dismissive attitude of the neighbors of her native town Moonstone, a fictional rural settlement in Colorado, remains faithful to her humble origins and to her ancestral Swedish heritage. That the Mexican community immediately recognizes the rough diamond of Thea’s untrained voice while the sophisticated audience of Chicago or New York fails to appreciate it brings forth Cather’s moral ideals and her glorification of the American dream, in which willpower, the culture of discipline, perseverance and self-sacrifice is a one-way ticket to success.<br /><br />But what truly spoke to my heart’s wish wasn’t the implacable resolution of its female protagonist or Cather’s polished, sensual style, which reaches moments of powerful emotion bathed with youthful, fresh enthusiasm. Neither did the eerie, lyrical passages describing vast prairies, canyons and sand dunes caressed by predawn morning sunbeams that give the familiar epic dimension to Cather’s stories, as bewitching as they are.<br />It was the masterful depiction of the growth of an artist, the tortuous journey required to recognize her gift and curse at once, and the inner process that unleashes her talent to its full potential that won me over completely and left me floating to the tessituras of a virtuous soprano performing the role of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Die_Walküre" rel="nofollow noopener">Sieglinde</a>, whose melody I managed to conjure from written words alone. An illusion? Or the power of a narrative that sprouts out from the intellectual and spiritual development of its creator? Maybe both. <br /><br />Whatever the reason, in my memory will linger the sensation of hearing the life-altering sound of a voice bringing an idea to life, of a voice becoming the instrument of such idea, an idea that levitates like a soft feather, never falling down on you like a dead weight, but being continually elevated until it is transformed into the shadow of an ancient eagle gliding majestically over the steep precipice of an Arizonian Canyon, summoning a chant to ancient lands and its people and their everlasting commitment to life, to art…to beauty.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4978252218632839888" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


