              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=relationships">relationships</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=usa">usa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=arts">arts</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=mexico">mexico</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=philo-psychol">philo-psychol</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=native-am">native-am</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2895133964" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11235688668844115222">Please, take the time to look at this painting by Jules Adolphe Aimé Louis Breton, a 19th-century French Naturalist painter: <br/><a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jules_Breton'>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jules_B...</a><br/>Scroll down a bit to get to the image of the painting. It inspired both Cather&apos;s book and its title. Cather has in word&apos;s captured the feel of Breton&apos;s paining. Isn&apos;t it wonderful?<br/><br/>What do you see when you look at the painting? I see a woman with grit and determination. Look at the uplifted jaw line. Look at the tilt of the head. That</span>
  <span id="freeText11235688668844115222" style="display:none">Please, take the time to look at this painting by Jules Adolphe Aimé Louis Breton, a 19th-century French Naturalist painter: <br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jules_Breton">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jules_B...</a><br />Scroll down a bit to get to the image of the painting. It inspired both Cather's book and its title. Cather has in word's captured the feel of Breton's paining. Isn't it wonderful?<br /><br />What do you see when you look at the painting? I see a woman with grit and determination. Look at the uplifted jaw line. Look at the tilt of the head. That young woman is Thea Kronborg, the central character of the novel. Music is her lifeblood. The book follows her from childhood in rural Colorado to her career as an internationally acclaimed opera singer.<br /><br />Look again at the painting. The torrid landscape, the orange sun, the bare feet and the simplicity of the woman’s attire mirror Thea’s existence in Moonstone, Colorado. Willa Cather transforms the visual into words. It is the book’s beautifully descriptive prose that attracts me most. Add to this pitch perfect dialogues. <br /><br />We watch as Thea matures. We watch as she grows from a child to an adult. We observe her transformation. Her thoughts and her manner of speech gradually alter, but she, her essence, her whole way of being, remain the same. The story is said to have autobiographical content. <br /><br />Thea’s closest childhood friends are kind Doctor Archie who is unhappily married, festive and life loving Mexicans residing in the “Mexican Village” nearby, Spanish Johnny, the Kohlers and Wunsch, Thea’s German piano teacher. Visiting the abodes of ancestral Pueblo cliff dwellers is an essential element of the plot. Look how Cather has chosen to place Thea within a circle of friends of many nationalities. Cather is saying that different cultures are equal in value and that the more one knows of how other people live, the richer is one’s life. The story fluidly interweaves different people’s customs, traditions and ways of being. Thea is of Swedish and Norwegian heritage. Later, in her career, she becomes a cosmopolitan, a woman of the world. <br /><br />We meet Ray Kennedy, another resident of Moonstone, a railway man of thirty. He has dreams of one day marrying Thea. This is when Thea is still twelve, at the start of the novel. Thea has an individuality that stands out and stood out to those around her. Her vitality enthralls not only her friends but also the heart of readers. <br /><br />Thea becomes a woman with an immensely strong work ethic. What will be sacrificed to attain her goals? Ultimately, will she be happy? Could she have lived her life any other way? These are the questions one asks. Who she is and who she becomes and how she gets there are realistically drawn. The tale feels genuine and real. <br /><br />Thea comes to leave Moonstone. She travels to Chicago, New York and abroad, but her ties to the American Southwest remain forever strong. <br /><br />Barbara Caruso does a fantastic job narrating the audiobook. Her performance definitely deserves five stars. She sings songs, recites poetry, captures different accents and characters of different ages, backgrounds and gender. All is done with flair. In my view, the narration simply could not be done better. It’s perfect. Well no, there is one flaw; she doesn’t accurately pronounce the Swedish name Gunnar, but this isn’t important. <br /><br />**********************<br />**********************<br /><br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17150.My__ntonia__Great_Plains_Trilogy___3_" title="My Ántonia (Great Plains Trilogy, #3) by Willa Cather" rel="nofollow noopener">My Ántonia</a> 5 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/545951.Death_Comes_for_the_Archbishop" title="Death Comes for the Archbishop by Willa Cather" rel="nofollow noopener">Death Comes for the Archbishop</a> 4 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/543137.One_of_Ours" title="One of Ours by Willa Cather" rel="nofollow noopener">One of Ours</a> 4 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/48214.The_Song_of_the_Lark__Great_Plains_Trilogy___2_" title="The Song of the Lark (Great Plains Trilogy, #2) by Willa Cather" rel="nofollow noopener">The Song of the Lark</a>4 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/599782.Lucy_Gayheart" title="Lucy Gayheart by Willa Cather" rel="nofollow noopener">Lucy Gayheart</a> 3 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/140963.O_Pioneers___Great_Plains_Trilogy___1_" title="O Pioneers! (Great Plains Trilogy, #1) by Willa Cather" rel="nofollow noopener">O Pioneers!</a> 3 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/48213.Sapphira_and_the_Slave_Girl" title="Sapphira and the Slave Girl by Willa Cather" rel="nofollow noopener">Sapphira and the Slave Girl</a> 2 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/48200.A_Lost_Lady" title="A Lost Lady by Willa Cather" rel="nofollow noopener">A Lost Lady</a> 2 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/48203.The_Professor_s_House" title="The Professor's House by Willa Cather" rel="nofollow noopener">The Professor's House</a> 2 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/834424.Shadows_on_the_Rock" title="Shadows on the Rock by Willa Cather" rel="nofollow noopener">Shadows on the Rock</a> TBR<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/445271.Alexander_s_Bridge" title="Alexander's Bridge by Willa Cather" rel="nofollow noopener">Alexander's Bridge</a> TBR<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/48211.My_Mortal_Enemy" title="My Mortal Enemy by Willa Cather" rel="nofollow noopener">My Mortal Enemy</a> TBR</span>
  <a data-text-id="11235688668844115222" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

