<div id="review_114396746" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/114396746" />
    <a title="Ensiform" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3843117-ensiform"><img alt="Ensiform" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1275973241p2/3843117.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/114396746?book_show_action=true">Jul 30, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ensiform" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ensiform" href="/user/show/3843117-ensiform">Ensiform</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3843117-ensiform?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer114396746" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7600876255854435368">Thea Kronborg, daughter of a minister in a small Colorado town, is discovered by the music teacher, a drunken German fellow, to have a rare gift. Sponsored by Archie, the town doctor and family friend, and Ray, a railroad man who intends to marry her but is killed, she travels to Chicago, then New Mexico, meeting more and more cosmopolitan people, until, at last, she is a star of the opera stage, and like a star radiant and very distant.<br/><br/>I found this book, at 420+ pages, quite a chore to get thro</span>
  <span id="freeText7600876255854435368" style="display:none">Thea Kronborg, daughter of a minister in a small Colorado town, is discovered by the music teacher, a drunken German fellow, to have a rare gift. Sponsored by Archie, the town doctor and family friend, and Ray, a railroad man who intends to marry her but is killed, she travels to Chicago, then New Mexico, meeting more and more cosmopolitan people, until, at last, she is a star of the opera stage, and like a star radiant and very distant.<br /><br />I found this book, at 420+ pages, quite a chore to get through. The character of Thea was utterly unsympathetic; her self-absorption even as a nobody is insufferable, and after she's a star, her melodramatic requirements are equally odious. The prose is tedious, as Cather fawns on her character, making her charismatic in the eyes of everyone except the reader. Actually, Thea is surrounded by sympathetic characters who lead interesting lives and are open, hearty, and engaging, but they all orbit around her, and Cather gives no reason for the reader to like her. Altogether a boring book, full of light and song but signifying nothing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7600876255854435368" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


