<div id="review_909339454" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/909339454" />
    <a title="Clif Hostetler" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/793473-clif-hostetler"><img alt="Clif Hostetler" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1593302055p2/793473.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/909339454?book_show_action=true">Apr 13, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Clif Hostetler" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Clif Hostetler" href="/user/show/793473-clif-hostetler">Clif Hostetler</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9781428196834" href="/book/show/3912321-the-song-of-the-lark">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/793473-clif-hostetler?shelf=novel">novel</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer909339454" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4071284616311247464">This novel is set in the late 19th to early 20th century and tells the story of a girl named Thea Kronborg from a rural town in eastern Colorado who has musical talent that attracts the attention of a series of mentors and sponsors. Through their help and support she&apos;s able to advance in the world of Wagnerian opera to become a world renowned diva. <br/><br/>Willa Cather&apos;s skilled writing portrays Thea&apos;s inner ambitious aspirations as she leaves small town life behind and becomes exposed to the cosmopolit</span>
  <span id="freeText4071284616311247464" style="display:none">This novel is set in the late 19th to early 20th century and tells the story of a girl named Thea Kronborg from a rural town in eastern Colorado who has musical talent that attracts the attention of a series of mentors and sponsors. Through their help and support she's able to advance in the world of Wagnerian opera to become a world renowned diva. <br /><br />Willa Cather's skilled writing portrays Thea's inner ambitious aspirations as she leaves small town life behind and becomes exposed to the cosmopolitan influences of Chicago. Cather devises a detour in the narrative that takes Thea to Arizona where she emerges from a canyon flash flood probably symbolizing rebirth into a new life. <br /><br />The narrative then jumps forward ten years, and Thea has returned to New York from a circuit of European opera singing. She is on the cusp to breaking through from "new young voice" to recognized "top tier voice" when she receives the chance of a life-time. She receives a telephone call asking if she can come to the Metropolitan Opera immediately and finish a performance where the lead soprano has become ill after the first act and can't finish. Of course Thea performs magnificently and brings the house down with applause. (This is based on an actual occurrence in the life of Olive Fremstad.)<br /><br />The book is filled with extensive ruminations by Thea and others on subjects such as the struggle to release the potential that's hiding inside one's self. They are thoughts that most readers can relate to if they are able to recall the feeling of being young with all possibilities for the future open. Every step and decision along the path of life narrows the range of future possibilities. In Thea's case she senses a destiny for something special but isn't certain what it will be. At first she studies piano until her instructor discovers that she has a voice. She is told that she's a good pianist, but she has the potential to be a world-class singer.<br /><br />Normally, I as a reader would be completely engrossed in a rags to riches story and would be cheering for the success of the main character. But Thea as portrayed in the story isn't totally likable. She is a perfectionist who's insensitive to the feelings to others who are less talented. Her focused attention on her own skills deprives her of friendship of others her own age. But perhaps these personality flaws provide a realistic representation of the personal cost of being goal oriented on a career that requires total devotion. The following is a quotation toward the end of the book of Thea reflecting on her career:<blockquote> Your work becomes your personal life. You are not much good until it does. Its like being woven into a big web. You can't pull away, because all your little tendrils are woven into the picture.</blockquote>The following link is to an essay by Richard Maurer that describes the friendship between Willa Cather and the famous opera singer Olive Fremstad who greatly influenced the content of this book:<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/masterpiece/americancollection/lark/tg_diva.html">http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/masterpiece/a...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="4071284616311247464" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


