    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1555483717" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1555483717" />
    <a title="Laysee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4863523-laysee"><img alt="Laysee" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1459741824p2/4863523.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1555483717?book_show_action=true">Feb 20, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laysee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laysee" href="/user/show/4863523-laysee">Laysee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Winston Ong</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1555483717" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16529644616202444631">“Nothing is far and nothing is near, if one desires. The world is little, people are little, human life is little. There is only one big thing - desire. And before it, when it is big, all is little.&quot; – Willa Cather<br/><br/>“The Song of the Lark” by Willa Cather is a novel after my own heart. When I stumbled on Dolors&apos; beautifully crafted review of this book by an author I have never read, I felt that knowing tug that signaled pleasure and promise. I was right.<br/><br/>Thea Kronborg, known as “Little Swede”, was t</span>
  <span id="freeText16529644616202444631" style="display:none">“Nothing is far and nothing is near, if one desires. The world is little, people are little, human life is little. There is only one big thing - desire. And before it, when it is big, all is little." – Willa Cather<br /><br />“The Song of the Lark” by Willa Cather is a novel after my own heart. When I stumbled on Dolors' beautifully crafted review of this book by an author I have never read, I felt that knowing tug that signaled pleasure and promise. I was right.<br /><br />Thea Kronborg, known as “Little Swede”, was the daughter of a humble preacher who had seven children. Thea had an extraordinary gift of music. Living in the obscure (fictional) town of Moonstone, Colorado, and given her family’s limited financial resources, Thea did not have early access to fine musical training. She took piano lessons from Professor Wunsch, a wandering musician who drank. Wunsch recognised Thea's talent - her "power of application, her rugged will". It was Wunsch who first introduced Thea to classical songs and a tiny window opened that fired in Thea a love of singing. Because I was a voice student, it brought back reminders of songs I’d learnt (e.g., “Eurydice” in Gluck’s Orpheus) and sent me looking up songs such as “Come Ye, Disconsolate” that Thea sang at her father’s church services. <br /><br />“The Song of the Lark” traced Thea’s arduous journey to become a professional singer. The roadblocks to realizing a dream seemed insurmountable because a gift, like a plant, cannot flourish except in the right soil. Even though Thea was intelligent and talented, her restricted opportunities for early training meant she was uncultivated and ignorant. Her first concert pianist teacher in Chicago (Andor Harsanyi) observed that Thea came to him “like a fine young savage, a book with nothing written in it." What were her chances of succeeding? I was swept up in Thea’s quest to become the best she can be as a musician. <br /><br />I was impressed by Thea’s tenacity, fighting spirit, discipline, and industry. Her strengths were her "unusual power of work", "her way of charging at difficulties as if they were foes she had long been seeking,.. as if they were destined for her and she for them." I enjoyed reading about her music lessons and reflected on how the student’s relationship with his/her mentor was all important in shaping both the gift and the professional attitude. (I am grateful for the nurturing and encouraging teachers I had; only one encounter with a critical diva at a Master's class was unpleasant.) It was Harsanyi who said, "When people, serious people, believe in you, they give you some of their best, so - take care of it, Miss Kronborg." With Madison Bowers, the best voice teacher in Chicago, who lacked warmth and generosity, Thea took on the grouchiness, skepticism, and contempt that Bowers modelled. <br /><br />I envied Thea her band of ardent supporters: her aunt Tillie, and the men - Ray Kennedy, Dr. Archie, Fred Ottenburg - who were all half smitten or head over heels in love with her. These, together with her teachers such as Wunsch, Harsanyi and Bowers, recognized and stretched her musical knowledge and skills. A few provided financial support that enabled her to hone her gift. Much as I admired her many fine qualities, Thea became less and less likeable as she matured. <br /><br />I felt elated when Thea was finally given the opportunity to sing the lead roles at the Metropolitan Opera House because the feted professionals were unavailable due to illness. Then I felt her panic when she had to rehearse in double quick time and hoped she would nail the role(s)so well she could secure future contracts and gain the recognition she deserved. Of course, there was overwhelming joy when she finally delivered a song that allowed her to shine or a performance where everything came together and bore distinctly her signature brilliance. <br /><br />Music aside, Cather wrote beautifully about the natural landscape. At Panther Canyon, Arizona, restoration of spirit could be found among the "yellow rocks baking in sunlight" and the cleansing solitude. The language in this novel (published in 1915) belonged to an earlier era and was genteelly elegant. Cather also painted character sketches that were vivid even for minor ones that were met in passing such as the Rev Larsen in Chicago.<br /><br />This is a novel that will resonate with music lovers, particularly individuals who understood from direct experience the challenges of singing to an audience. Music aside, there’s something in this book for everyone. Because like Thea Kronborg, many of us have dreams and understand the struggles toward actualization that are common to all and yet unique to our own experience.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16529644616202444631" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


