    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2785428818" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2785428818" />
    <a title="Joe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/715626-joe"><img alt="Joe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1366845516p2/715626.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2785428818?book_show_action=true">Apr 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joe" href="/user/show/715626-joe">Joe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/715626-joe?shelf=listened-to">listened-to</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2785428818" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18394354382283216835">Growing up, Willa Cather was my favorite author but it had been FAR too long since I&apos;d read anything by her and so when I saw this on the shelf at my local library, I snapped it right up. &quot;The Song of the Lark&quot; is Willa Cather&apos;s take on the &quot;Brain Drain.&quot; For those not from the Midwest, the &quot;Brain Drain&quot; is the phenomenon of the best and the brightest of a small town/state moving away to a larger city/state. It&apos;s clear from this book that this issue isn&apos;t new and isn&apos;t likely to go away in the f</span>
  <span id="freeText18394354382283216835" style="display:none">Growing up, Willa Cather was my favorite author but it had been FAR too long since I'd read anything by her and so when I saw this on the shelf at my local library, I snapped it right up. "The Song of the Lark" is Willa Cather's take on the "Brain Drain." For those not from the Midwest, the "Brain Drain" is the phenomenon of the best and the brightest of a small town/state moving away to a larger city/state. It's clear from this book that this issue isn't new and isn't likely to go away in the foreseeable future.<br /><br />Our protagonist is Thea Kronborg, a musical prodigy. She first leaves her small town to pursue the piano in Chicago but it quickly becomes clear that her true talent lies in her singing. The story is basically Thea following her dream and those who support her. This is more of a character study than anything else. Plot wise, there's not much there: A talented person works hard and succeeds. What makes the book standout is the fantastic writing and feminist themes which were WAY ahead of their time. I highly recommend this delightful read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18394354382283216835" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


